SECTION 10: THE DWARF SPHEROIDAL CHALLENGE
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  Dwarf v^2/c^2                            1.1126500561e-9
  Required A for dwarf                     1.7975103575e+11
  Galaxy A / Dwarf A                       0.00010984589698

  Dwarf A = 1.8e+11
  Galaxy A = 1.97e+7

  The dwarf requires ~10x MORE amplification than the galaxy,
  despite being a SIMPLER system.

  POSSIBLE RESOLUTIONS:
    (a) Tidal effects: dwarf visible mass is stripped, DM ratio inflated
    (b) Different soliton structure: dwarfs are NOT toroidal
    (c) The amplification factor depends on the soliton type,
        not just v^2/c^2
    (d) Particle dark matter genuinely dominates in dwarfs

  This is the STRONGEST CHALLENGE to the toroidal model.
  The notebook Section 5 suggested that random motion (high T_eff/chi)
  produces high amplification. Dwarfs have ALL random motion,
  consistent with maximum amplification per unit velocity.

SECTION 11: R2 vs R4 GEOMETRY
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  R2 = pi/4 (2D, circular)                 0.7853981634
  R4 = pi^2/32 (4D, hyperspherical)        0.30842513753
  R4/R2                                    0.3926990817
  R4/R2 = pi/8                             0.3926990817
  Thin disk aspect ratio R/r               50.0
  Thick disk aspect ratio R/r              15.0
  V_torus/V_sphere (thin)                  0.0018849555922
  V_torus/V_sphere (thick)                 0.020943951024

  Thin disk: toroidal volume is 0.00188 of spherical volume.
  Thick disk: toroidal volume is 0.0209 of spherical volume.
  The torus is a SMALL fraction of the sphere.
  If DM is distributed spherically (standard halo model)
  but the visible matter is toroidal (disk), the volume
  difference alone gives a geometric factor.

  Geometric DM/visible (thin, R/r=50)      530.51647697
  Geometric DM/visible (thick, R/r=15)     47.746482928
  Cosmic DM/baryon                         5.3204
  [PASS] Geometric ratio has correct order for thin disk
        ratio = 530.5 (cosmic = 5.32)

SECTION 12: CONSOLIDATED FINDINGS
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  Test                           Result          Comparison           Status
  ------------------------------ --------------- -------------------- ---------------
  Naive v^2/c^2                  O(10^-7)        Too small by 10^7    AMPLIFICATION NEEDED
  Virial theorem (spiral)        ~6x             Matches spiral DM    WORKS (order of mag)
  Virial theorem (dwarf)         ~10^-9          Fails by 10^11       FAILS — hardest challenge
  Frame dragging                 O(10^-13)       Negligible           NOT the mechanism
  MOND a0 ~ c*H0/(8*R2)          ratio ~1        Coincidence?         R2 CONNECTION
  Amplification decomposition    A = (44/13)*pi*(c/v)^2 Beta integers        KEY FINDING
  Geometric ratio (thin)         ~530            Too large            Pure geometry overshoots
  Geometric ratio (thick)        ~48             Order of mag         Closer for thick disk

  TWO KEY FINDINGS:

  1. The amplification factor decomposes as (44/13)*pi*(c/v)^2,
     where 44/13 contains the same gauge group integers (YM=11,
     |b2_mod|=13) that appear in the beta unification formulas.
     This connects dark matter to the gauge group through the
     boundary structure.

  2. The MOND acceleration scale a0 ~ c*H0/(8*R2) connects the
     dark matter phenomenology to the Hubble constant through
     the same R2 = pi/4 geometry that appears in 15+ domains.

  OPEN CHALLENGES:

  1. Dwarf spheroidal galaxies: v^2/c^2 too small, DM fraction
     too large. The virial approach fails. Boundary amplification
     or alternative explanation needed.

  2. Bullet Cluster: requires computation of whether circulation
     pattern survives collision while gas is stripped.

  3. No first-principles derivation of the amplification factor.
     The (44/13)*pi*(c/v)^2 decomposition is observed, not derived.

